Lets install MinGW :
MinGW-w64 (The Engine)
MinGW provides the GCC (GNU Compiler Collection), which is what actually turns your human-readable code into a .exe file.
Crucial Step: You must add the bin folder of your MinGW installation (usually C:\mingw64\bin) to your System Environment Variables (PATH). Without this, VS Code won't know where the compiler lives.
Verification: Open a terminal and type gcc --version. If it spits out a version number, you're good to go.

VS Code (The Cockpit) :
VS Code is just a fancy text editor until you give it "C powers."
The Extension: Go to the Extensions view ($Ctrl+Shift+X$) and install the C/C++ Extension Pack by Microsoft. 
This gives you IntelliSense (code completion) and debugging.
The Runner: Most beginners love the Code Runner extension. It adds a "Play" button to the top right so you can run your code with one click instead of typing commands manually.